The executore of a testator and administratore osan intestate have the same remedy for injury to the personal property of the deceased as he would have had in his lifetime.

For an injury committed against his real property within six months of his death, they may bring an action within one year after his death. And for an injury to either real or personal property committed within six months before the death of the wrong-doer, an action may be brought against his executore or administratore within six months after they have taken on themselves adminis- tration.

á¾§ 114. Respecting the power of absolution, J ustinian confirmed the opinion of the Sabinianus, Inst. 4, 12, 2.

The principle, Omnia judicia esse absolutoria indicates an ex- ception to the effecte of Litis contestatio. The motive of the effecte ascribed to Litis contestatio is in general to avert from the plaintiff the injurious consequences of the protracted duration of a trial. Accordingly if judgment passed in his favour he was put into the position he would have occupied if J udgment had immediately fol- lowed on litis contestatio.
